I would like to use this as well, but as this isnt an option i can offer a hack for some.  You can use a data editor where the default week start is monday, with a single row and single column and then pass this value to a datetime or whatever you need. 

`d_pandas = st.data_editor(
    pd.DataFrame({'date': [date_default]}),
    num_rows=1,
    column_config={
        'date': st.column_config.DateColumn(
            'date', min_value=date(2023, 8, 1), required=True, format="DD-MM-YYYY", width='medium'
        )
    },
    hide_index=True
).iloc[0,0]

d = st.date_input("date", date_default)`

Hope this is helpful

Just tried out the `locale` setting in BaseWeb real quick. It indeed adapts the starting day correctly based on the country. E.g. for the code below that sets a German locale, the week in the resulting date picker starts on Monday.

```javascript
import * as React from "react";
import { DatePicker } from "baseui/datepicker";
import { de } from "date-fns/locale"; // Import German locale

import { Client as Styletron } from "styletron-engine-monolithic";
import { Provider as StyletronProvider } from "styletron-react";
import { LightTheme, BaseProvider, styled } from "baseui";

const engine = new Styletron();

const Centered = styled("div", {
  display: "flex",
  justifyContent: "center",
  alignItems: "center",
  height: "100%",
});

export default () => {
  const [value, setValue] = React.useState([new Date()]);

  return (
    <StyletronProvider value={engine}>
      <BaseProvider theme={LightTheme}>
        <Centered>
          <DatePicker
            value={value}
            onChange={({ date }) =>
              setValue(Array.isArray(date) ? date : [date])
            }
            locale={de} // Set the locale to German
            displayValueAtRangeIndex={0}
          />
        </Centered>
      </BaseProvider>
    </StyletronProvider>
  );
};
```

![CleanShot 2024-01-18 at 23 02 07](https://github.com/streamlit/streamlit/assets/127552870/36aff32b-0af5-4e41-a550-2e8cbe15193a)

Unfortunately, it doesn't automatically set the date format shown in the input box to the German format (which would be 09.02.2024 for the example above). So either:

1. we'd require users to set both the locale and the date format manually (using the `format` parameter) or 
2. we make something that internally sets the correct format for a given locale. 

(2) would probably be nicer from a developer's point of view but also means more work. Might be interesting to see if there's a way in date-fns to retrieve the correct format for a given locale. Maybe we could also ship (1) in the meantime to unblock users and do (2) later on (since it won't really break anything).
